    <h4>What is Face Detection?</h4>
    <p>Before recognition can happen the system must <em>locate</em> every face in the image and return bounding boxes. It is a dense binary classification problem — face vs background — solved at every position and scale.</p>
    <h4>🕰 Classical: Viola-Jones (2001)</h4>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Haar-like features</strong> measure brightness differences between rectangular image regions — e.g. eyes are darker than cheeks, the nose bridge is lighter than the sides. Over 160,000 features exist per detection window.</li>
      <li><strong>Integral Image</strong> pre-computes cumulative pixel sums so any rectangular region sum requires exactly 4 lookups — O(1) regardless of size.</li>
      <li><strong>AdaBoost + Cascade</strong> selects the 200 most discriminative features and chains them: cheap early stages reject ~99.9% of non-face windows so expensive later stages only run on the rare remaining candidates.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="hbox hb-y">⚡ Viola-Jones achieved 15 fps on 2001 hardware. It is still shipped in OpenCV today. Its main limitation: reliable only within ±30° of frontal pose.</div>
    <h4>🤖 Neural: SSD MobileNet v1 (used in this tool)</h4>
    <p><strong>Single Shot Detector</strong> with a lightweight <strong>MobileNet</strong> backbone. A single forward pass through the CNN simultaneously predicts bounding boxes and confidence scores at multiple scales using pre-defined anchor boxes. Non-Maximum Suppression removes duplicate detections. Trained on millions of labelled faces.</p>
