    <h4>The Core Problem</h4>
    <p>Compress a face image (e.g. 150×150 = 22,500 pixels) to a compact vector where same-identity faces cluster together and different identities are far apart — under all lighting, expression, and pose variations.</p>
    <h4>🕰 Eigenfaces — PCA (Turk &amp; Pentland 1991)</h4>
    <p>Apply PCA to a matrix of flattened face images. The K principal eigenvectors (eigenfaces) define a face subspace. Each new image is projected onto this subspace:</p>
    <div class="formula">f = Wᵀ(x − μ) &nbsp;&nbsp; W = [e₁ … eₖ] eigenvectors</div>
    <p>Works in controlled studio light; fails when lighting changes because PCA encodes illumination variation as identity difference.</p>
    <h4>🕰 HOG + LBP</h4>
    <p><strong>HOG</strong> (Histogram of Oriented Gradients) divides the image into 8×8 cells, computes gradient direction histograms per cell, normalises across 2×2 block groups → illumination-invariant edge descriptor. <strong>LBP</strong> (Local Binary Pattern) compares each pixel to its 8 neighbours, encodes as an 8-bit number, histograms over the face grid. Both feed a linear SVM. Still used in embedded systems for their speed.</p>
    <h4>🤖 ResNet-34 + Triplet Loss (used here)</h4>
    <p>A 34-layer <strong>Residual Network</strong> trained using <strong>triplet loss</strong> on millions of face pairs. Given anchor A, positive P (same person, different photo), negative N (different person):</p>
    <div class="formula">L = max(0, ‖f(A)−f(P)‖² − ‖f(A)−f(N)‖² + α)</div>
    <p>The network learns a 128-dimensional embedding where same-identity faces sit within distance 0.6 and different identities sit further. The vladmandic model is converted from dlib's <code>dlib_face_recognition_resnet_model_v1</code>.</p>
